			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="744">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I found it hard to believe Alan Craig&rsquo;s claim, in his essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4495">Everything&rsquo;s Going to Be OK</a>&rdquo; [January 2011], that he and his friends are in their sixties. From his descriptions of all their illnesses, mishaps, and near-death experiences, I thought surely they were at least in their eighties. How will he manage to survive if he actually does reach that age? He&rsquo;ll be lucky if his wife hangs around that long to listen to his whining. I have no sympathy for a person with such an intolerant attitude toward his mother&rsquo;s request to drive her to her doctor. Where is his compassion? Hopefully she doesn&rsquo;t read <em>The Sun</em>.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Trudy Goldman<br>Marina del Rey, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="745">
								<p><a href="/contributors/alan-craig"><strong>Alan Craig</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>Reading Goldman&rsquo;s letter caused me to laugh, mostly at myself. It&rsquo;s worse than she thinks: I won&rsquo;t be sixty for another couple of weeks. I&rsquo;m sure if my old friends Roger, Jason, and Eddie were still around today they&rsquo;d beg Goldman&rsquo;s pardon for dying so young.</p>

<p>As to my lack of compassion toward my mother, I can only say that I try to be a good son and that I fail much more often than I&rsquo;d like. If Goldman is free of all ambivalent feelings when it comes to her own family members, I congratulate her.</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t know how I&rsquo;ll ever cope with being really old if and when the time comes. It&rsquo;s an excellent question, and the point of my essay.</p>
	</div>


								<div class="block-correspondence" id="710">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I just finished reading Trudy Goldman&rsquo;s comments [<a href="/issues/424/correspondence">Correspondence</a> April 2011] on Alan Craig&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4495">Everything&rsquo;s Going to Be OK</a>&rdquo; [January 2011]. As a previously very athletic person now in my late sixties, I&rsquo;m in complete accord with Craig, who finds it tough to bear the physical discomforts as he approaches sixty and wonders how he will manage in his seventies and eighties. All those doctors&rsquo; appointments and treatments that my elders put up with seem intolerable to me. I keep thinking that people must go through some amazing transformation in their eighties to value whatever life they still have. I hope that is true, because my current mindset will not get me through.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Joanna Friesen<br>Houston, Texas</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

